Read the learning2014 data from my local folder into RStudio

learning2014 <- read.table("H:/Jatko-opinnot/Open data science/IODS-project/data/learning2014", sep=",", header=TRUE)

Data is from international survey of Approaches to Learning and data is collected 3.12.2014 - 10.1.2015

There are 166 observations (rows) and 8 variables (columns). First column has row numbers as integer. Columns age and points are also as integers and columns attitude, deep, stra and surf as numerical. Gender is a factor with 2 levels.

Variables: gender: gender of respondent, M = male, F = female age: age of the respondent attitude: global attitude towards statistics deep: average of answers to questions related to deep learning stra: average of answers to questions related to strategic learning surf: average of answers to questions related to surface learning points: exam points

Remove the first column from the data because it is not needed. First choose the columns to keep

There are twice as many women than man in the data. Youngest student in 17 and oldets 55 mean age being 25.5. Men are in average older than women. Mens attitude is on higher level than womens. On deep questions men have given sligthly bigger values than women. On strategic and surface questions women have given bigger values than men. There are hardly any difference in points between men and women.

Highest positive correlation can be found between points and attitude (0.437). This means that attitude explains the points the student gets by 44%. Highest negative correalation is between surface and deep question.

All variables are quite normally distributed except age where most students are quite young (3/4 under 27 years old).

I choose variables attitude, strategic questions (stra) and surface questions (surf) as explanatory variables to explain the exam points and fit a regression model

mymodel <- lm (points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
summary(mymodel)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -17.1550  -3.4346   0.5156   3.6401  10.8952 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.0171     3.6837   2.991  0.00322 ** 
## attitude      3.3952     0.5741   5.913 1.93e-08 ***
## stra          0.8531     0.5416   1.575  0.11716    
## surf         -0.5861     0.8014  -0.731  0.46563    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.296 on 162 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2074, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1927 
## F-statistic: 14.13 on 3 and 162 DF,  p-value: 3.156e-08

Residuals seem quite evenly distributed with median close to zero and first and third quantile almost evenly far from the median. Minimun value is almost twice as far from median than the maximum value but we can still say that residuals seem ok.

The estimate for attitude tells that when attitude increses 1 unit the points increase by 3.3952 units. p-value is very small, so we can say with high confidense that attitude effects the points. For strategic questions the estimate is 0.8531 and for surface questions -0.5861 but for these varaibles the p-values are quite large (0.11716 and 0.46563) so these varaibles dont have an effect on points.

Multiple R-squared tells that 20.74% of variability in points is explained by these three variables.

Because variables stra and surf do not have a statistically significant relationship with the points variable these are removed from the model

mymodel2 <- lm (points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
summary(mymodel2)

Again, residuals seen to be ok.

Estimate for attitude is now a bit higher (3.5255) than in the previous model and p-value is even smaller.

Multiple R-squared is almost as hig as before (19.06).

Excluding the stra and surf variables from the model doesnt really change the goodnes of the model so the variables can be left out.

Diagnostic plots: Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage

par(mfrow = c(2,2)) 
plot(mymodel2, which = c(1, 2, 5))

Assumptions of linear model: .The errors are normally distributed .The errors are not correlated .The errors have constant variance, ??2 .The size of a given error does not depend on the explanatory variables

Residual vs Fitted values: Size of an error is not dependent on fitted values > model is ok

Normal QQ-plot: Errors of the model are nicely normally distributed > model is ok

Residuals vs Leverage: None observation has an unusually high impact > model is ok

Data has information about student alcohol consumption. The original data set can be found here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/STUDENT+ALCOHOL+CONSUMPTION

There are 382 observations (rows) and 36 variables (columns) in the data. The variables include information about alcohol consumption and also social, gender and study time attributes.

I chose the following 4 variables to study the relationship between them and alcohol consumption level:

14 studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours) 19 activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no) 29 health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good) 30 absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)

My hypothesis: High weekly study time is associated with low alcohol consumption Having extra-curricular activities is associated with low alcohol consumption Better health is associated with low alcohol consumption The higher the number of absences the larger proportion of students have high alcohol consumption

My hypothesis: The higher the number of absences the larger proportion of students have high alcohol consumption Result: True: Students with low alcohol consumption has fewer absences

The Boston data has 506 observations and 14 variables. Most of the variables are numerical, but chas and rad are integers.

The variables are described as follows:

crim = per capita crime rate by town.

zn = proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

indus = proportion of non-retail business acres per town.

chas = Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).

nox = nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).

rm = average number of rooms per dwelling.

age = proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.

dis = weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.

rad = index of accessibility to radial highways.

tax = full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.

ptratio = pupil-teacher ratio by town.

black = 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.

lstat = lower status of the population (percent).

medv = median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

The varaibles are now around zero (mean = 0)

Create a categorical variable of the crime rate

Save the scaled crim variable as scaled_crim

scaled_crim <- boston_scaled$crim

Create a quantile vector of crim

bins <- quantile(scaled_crim)

Create a categorical variable crime

crime <- cut(scaled_crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

Remove original crim from the dataset

boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

Add the new categorical value to scaled data

boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

Divide the dataset to training and test sets

Place number of rows in the Boston dataset to n

n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

Choose randomly 80% of the rows

ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

Create training set

train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

Create test set

test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Fit the linear discriminant analysis on the training set

Fit the LDA and use the crime rate as the target variable and other variables as predictor variables

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

The function for lda biplot arrows

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

Set classes as numeric

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

Draw the LDA plot

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

Save the correct classes from test data

correct_classes <- test$crime

Remove the crime variable from test data

test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

Predict classes with test data

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

Reload the Boston data and standardize it and set it as data frame

data("Boston")
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)

Calculate the distances between the observations. Here I use euclidean distance matrix (default in the dist function)

dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled)

Run k-means algorithm on the data

Determine the number of clusters

k_max <- 10

Calculate and visualize the total within sum of squares to see the optimal number of clusters

twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_eu, k)$tot.withinss})
plot(1:k_max, twcss, type='b')

Three clusters seems to be the right amount of clusters, or maybe four. Lets go with three!

Do the k-means clustering

km <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 3)

Visualize the clusters

pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

The human data has 155 observations and 8 variables. It combines indicators from most countries. Countries are the row names.

Health and knowledge indicators:
GNI = Gross National Income per capita
Life.Exp = Life expectancy at birth
Edu.Exp = Expected years of schooling
Mat.Mor = Maternal mortality ratio
Ado.Birth = Adolescent birth rate

Empowerment indicators:
Parli.F = Percetange of female representatives in parliament
Edu2.F = Proportion of females with at least secondary education
Edu2.M = Proportion of males with at least secondary education
Labo.F = Proportion of females in the labour force
Labo.M " Proportion of males in the labour force

New indicators:
Edu2.FM = Edu2.F / Edu2.M = Ratio of female and male populations with secondary education
Labo.FM = Labo2.F / Labo2.M = Ratio of labour force participation of females and males

PCA on standardized human data

Standardize the data

human_std <- scale(human)
pca_human_std <- prcomp(human_std)

Variance captured by each PC

s_std <- summary(pca_human_std)
pca_pr_std <- round(100*s_std$importance[2, ], digits = 2)
pca_pr_std
##   PC1   PC2   PC3   PC4   PC5   PC6   PC7   PC8 
## 53.61 16.24  9.57  7.58  5.48  3.60  2.63  1.30

Biplot

pc_lab_std <- paste0(names(pca_pr_std), " (", pca_pr_std, "%)")
biplot(pca_human_std, cex = c(0.5, 1.5), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), xlab = (pc_lab_std[1]) , ylab = pc_lab_std[2])

Without standardizing the data 99.99 % of variance was explained by the first PC. This is not a believable outcome of PCA. After standardizing the data the first PC explains most (53.61 %) of variance which is normal in PCA.

The first component is described on other hand by maternal mortality ratio and adolescent birth rate. These variables are highly correlated which can be seen from the arrows: there is only a small angle between them. This can be interpreted so that giving birth when adolescent mortality at birth is high. On other hand the first component is described by expected years of schooling, life expectancy at birth, ratio of females and males with secondary education and GNI. These four variables are higly correlated. This can be interpreted so that when education is at hig level, also for women, people tend to live longer and the nation has high gross national income per capita or vice versa.

The first component indicates that when maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate are high schooling, life expectancy, women schooling and GNI are low and vice versa.

The second component (16.24 % of variance) is explained by percetange of female representatives in parliament and ratio of labour force participation of females and males which are quite highly correlated with each other.
